  "参数有两种来源:查询串和路径": "Parameters come from two places: the query string and the path",
  "客户端把数据塞进请求的方式不止一种。最常见的两种:一是查询参数,挂在 URL 问号后面,像 /greet?name=Allen;二是路径变量,直接长在路径里,像 /users/42。它们语义不同——查询参数通常是「可选的筛选/配置」,路径变量通常是「定位某个资源的 ID」。Spring 用不同的注解分别接住它们。": "Clients pack data into a request in more than one way. The two most common: query parameters, hung after the question mark in the URL like /greet?name=Allen; and path variables, baked right into the path like /users/42. They mean different things — a query param is usually an 'optional filter/config', while a path variable is usually 'the ID that locates a resource'. Spring catches each with a different annotation.",
  "@RequestParam 绑查询参数": "@RequestParam binds query parameters",
  "在方法参数前写 @RequestParam,Spring 会从查询串里按名字找同名的值,自动做类型转换(字符串转成 int、long 等)。默认是必填的:请求没带这个参数就报 400 Bad Request。想让它可选,可以写 @RequestParam(required = false) 或给个 defaultValue。": "Put @RequestParam before a method parameter and Spring looks up the value by name in the query string, converting the type automatically (String to int, long, etc.). It's required by default: if the request omits the param, you get a 400 Bad Request. To make it optional, write @RequestParam(required = false) or supply a defaultValue.",
  "GET /greet?name=Allen 会得到 \"Hi, Allen\"": "GET /greet?name=Allen yields \"Hi, Allen\"",
  "URL 变量名和方法参数名一致时,@RequestParam 不用再写名字;不一致时要写 @RequestParam(\"name\")。": "When the URL variable name matches the method parameter name, @RequestParam needs no explicit name; when they differ, write @RequestParam(\"name\").",
  "@PathVariable 绑路径变量": "@PathVariable binds path variables",
  "路径变量分两步:先在映射里用花括号声明占位,@GetMapping(\"/users/{id}\");再在参数前用 @PathVariable 接住它。占位名和参数名一致时最省心。路径变量天生是「URL 的一部分」,所以它总是必填的——这正符合「用 ID 定位资源」的语义。": "Path variables take two steps: first declare the placeholder with braces in the mapping, @GetMapping(\"/users/{id}\"); then capture it with @PathVariable before the parameter. It's easiest when the placeholder name and parameter name match. A path variable is inherently 'part of the URL', so it's always required — which fits the 'locate a resource by ID' semantics.",
